<DESCRIPT>  STOCK; INDUSTRY; DECREASE; CHART  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Stocks fell in heavy trading Friday.;   The Dow Jones industrial average
closed down 12.75 for the day at 3,056.35, but it was up 51.43 for the week.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DOW DROPS 12.75  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     A sluggish report on jobs and a decline in the Index of Leading Economic
Indicators spurred hopes that the Fed would quickly ease credit, but when it
became apparent that it would not happen Friday, stock prices fell.;   Volume
on the New York Stock Exchange was 206.5 million shares, up from 182.2 million
on Thursday. Losing issues outnumbered gainers by 845 to 772.;   The Standard
&amp; Poor's 500-stock index fell 1.14 to 391.32, and the Big Board composite
droped 0.53 to 216.01. The American Stock Exchange composite fell 0.46 to
386.85.;   The NASDAQ composite index was off 2.05 to 540.93, while the
Russell 2000 was off 0.35 to 184.62.;   The Food and Drug Administration's
approval of Palo Alto-based Syntex's Ticlopidine, which reduces the risk of
strokes, moved the stock as high as 46 1/4 on Friday before it closed down 1/8
at 45 5/8.;   Alteon, a new issue, which was priced Thursday night at 15,
opened Friday at 26 1/2 and promptly ran to 30. It closed at 28 3/4 and topped
the NASDAQ most-active list with 4.7 million shares traded.;   AST Research
lost 2 1/8 to 19 1/2, while Dell Computer sank 2 1/4 to 22 5/8 on what traders
said was continued concern about competition in the personal computer
business.;   Borland International continued the rally that began after
analysts made positive comments yesterday. The stock rose 2 3/8 to 69 3/4 on
2.9 million shares.; Local stocks; Company       Boole &amp; Babbage; Amount up   
